###Steps 2-3

We can substitute $\blueE{FH=8}$, $\goldE{GH=6}$, $\maroonD{JH=6}$, and $\purpleD{IH=4}$ into $\dfrac{\blueE{FH}}{\goldE{GH}}$ and $\dfrac{\maroonD{JH}}{\purpleD{IH}}$:

$\begin{align}
&\dfrac{\blueE{FH}}{\goldE{GH}}=\dfrac{\blueE{8}}{\goldE{6}}
\\\\
&\dfrac{\maroonD{JH}}{\purpleD{IH}}=\dfrac{\maroonD{6}}{\purpleD{4}}
\end{align}$

Steps 2-3 are correct.

###Steps 2-4

We can substitute $\blueE{AC=20}$, $\goldE{CD=6}$, $\maroonD{BC=8}$, and $\purpleD{CE=15}$ into $\dfrac{\blueE{AC}}{\goldE{CD}}$ and $\dfrac{\maroonD{BC}}{\purpleD{CE}}$:

$\begin{align}
&\dfrac{\blueE{AC}}{\goldE{CD}}=\dfrac{\blueE{20}}{\goldE{6}}=3.\overline{3}
\\\\
&\dfrac{\maroonD{BC}}{\purpleD{CE}}=\dfrac{\maroonD{8}}{\purpleD{15}}=0.5\overline{3}
\end{align}$

So steps 2 and 3 are correct, and since $3.\overline{3}\neq 0.5\overline{3}$, step 4 is correct as well.

Nevertheless, Zheng did do something wrong here. While the calculations here are correct, the lengths compared are not of corresponding sides. Since $\overline{AC}$ and $\overline{CE}$ are the longer sides in each triangle, they correspond to each other.
